      {
        "id": 63008,
        "name": "",
        "username": "Herohtar",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/herohtar/{size}/43780_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-05-11T05:57:26.635Z",
        "cooked": "<p>‚ÄúProperly securing‚Äù means using a strong account password, enabling full disk encryption, always locking/logging out, etc. If you do those things, it will be very difficult for someone to access the data on it. If your computer is lost, and someone happens upon it and casually decides to snoop, they will be unable to do so. Clearing data would not provide any benefit in that scenario since they already can‚Äôt access it.</p>\n<p>Of course, if your computer is stolen by someone who is intent on getting your data, it is possible they can exploit some vulnerability or brute force the encryption to get to it. You might think that would be a case for remote data deletion, but I would still argue no ‚Äì if they were skilled enough to exploit vulnerabilities or break encryption, they are likely knowledgeable enough to keep the computer isolated offline in order to prevent any such remote wipe commands.</p>",
