      {
        "id": 63036,
        "name": "",
        "username": "sunu27",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2020-05-11T17:53:28.096Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I agree with your definition of properly securing, but I‚Äôm not your average mainstream (Windows/Apple/Ubuntu) user, which is why we know what things like ‚Äúenabling full disk encryption‚Äù mean.  Signal is clearly targeting the average mainstream user - I mean, even ‚ÄúLinux‚Äù on <a href=\"http://signal.org\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">signal.org</a> is synonymous with ‚ÄúDebian-based distros like Ubuntu.‚Äù  This is a major factor contributing to its success (maybe it‚Äôs a bit extreme, but let‚Äôs face it - people who don‚Äôt use Debian/Red hat based distros generally can look for build instructions in the README anyway).  So your first sentence is obviously true, but my hope for your average mainstream user getting their computer stolen is simply that their computer was locked.  Anyway, that‚Äôs tangential - you‚Äôre right about what everyone should do, as those are clearly reasonable precautions.  That does not, however, guarantee it will be very difficult for someone to access.  If your computer gets stolen, I would hope that it takes a really long time for the software to get outdated so that a vulnerability can be easily exploited.  If and only if that scenario, you‚Äôre right about ‚Äúvery difficult.‚Äù  I think the difference in our perspectives comes from how we think about hackers.  Maybe you and your friends are skilled hackers, so that‚Äôs what comes to your mind.  I don‚Äôt think the majority are really that skilled, though - I think for every true hacker out there programming tools to leverage exploits, there‚Äôs a ton of wannabes who just run their tools and call themselves ‚Äúhackers.‚Äù  And that‚Äôs assuming such an exploit - brute force might require a cloud, which would give further probability to internet access.  I don‚Äôt know what the probability might be, it‚Äôs probably not top priority, but I do think it‚Äôs a worthy consideration.</p>",
